      "id": "GENUS_PRIODONTES",
      "name": "Priodontes",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "The giant armadillo — the world's largest armadillo, reaching 1.5 m in length and weighing up to 60 kg. It has up to 100 small teeth — more than any other land mammal — arranged in rows but used minimally, as it tears apart termite mounds with massive, curved third claws and laps up insects with a long, sticky tongue. The giant armadillo is largely nocturnal and extremely secretive; its population is so sparse that it was barely studied until recent camera-trap surveys. It creates burrows large enough for a human to enter, which are subsequently used as critical shelters for dozens of other species including maned wolves, giant anteaters, tapirs, and pumas.",
